I recommend reading about the Activity lifecycle, specifically the part about saving and restoring UI state, which can be found [here][1]. Basically, you need to save your UI state in ```onSaveInstanceState()```.

EDIT: What happens right now is that the ```EditText``` value is not saved since you called ```super.onSaveInstanceState(state)``` first. Save the ```EditText``` value first to the ```Bundle```, then call ```super.onSaveInstanceState(state)```:

    @Override
    protected void onSaveInstanceState(Bundle State) {
        State.putCharSequence(&quot;key&quot; , txt.getText());
        super.onSaveInstanceState(State);
    }

 Then on your ```onRestoreINstanceState```, you don&#39;t have to call ```super```, you can just grab the saved value and set it immediately to your ```EditText```.


  [1]: https://developer.android.com/guide/components/activities/activity-lifecycle#saras

